    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-11-23T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-11-23T11:00:00-05:00" n="757"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d757">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00115 European War/11–2344: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kennan</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-11-23T19:00:00+03:00"
                            >November 23, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 23—3:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>4456. The first section of the Department’s 2695, November 18, 6 p.m.,<note
                        n="98" xml:id="d757fn98">See telegram 3921, November 18, 6 p.m., to Bern,
                        and footnote 94, <ref target="#pg_1218">p. 1218</ref>.</note> which was sent
                    through commercial channels and consequently was received a day later than
                    section 2, transmitted through Army facilities, contains no reference to my 4235
                    of November 4.<note n="99" xml:id="d757fn99">See <ref target="#pg_1218">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid</hi>
                        </ref>., and footnote 93, <ref target="#pg_1218">p. 1218</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>At one time or another, we have supplied the Soviet Government with a list of
                    American citizens in Hungary, have informed it that the Americans in Budapest
                    might decide to concentrate in the Venta Sanitarium, and have requested that
                    this information be transmitted to the competent Soviet military authorities and
                    that the latter make every effort to assure the safety of the persons in
                    question. A further communication on the subject to the Foreign Office therefore
                    does not appear to be necessary at this time.</p>
                <p>The action which the British Embassy has been instructed to take regarding the
                    protection of British subjects in Budapest is substantially similar to that
                    which we have already taken with respect to our own citizens.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennan</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
